<p><a name="Proverbs"></a><font color="#006600"><font size="+2">Approaches
to Narrative</font></font> <br>
<b><font color="#000099"><font size="+1">Notes Towards a Bibliography</font></font></b> <br>
(revised 25 May 2001) <br>
<img src="../../Images/Rule10.gif" nosave="" height="20" vspace="40" width="90%"> <br>
<font size="+1"><a href="#Narrative">Narratology</a></font>&nbsp;&nbsp;
|&nbsp;&nbsp; <font size="+1"><a href="#Cognitive">Cognitive Approaches</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;
|&nbsp; <a href="#Neuroscience">Neurology</a></font></p>
</center>
<p><a name="Narrative"></a><font color="#009900"><font size="+1">Narratology</font></font> </p>
<p>Bal, Mieke. <i>Narratology: Introduction to the Theory of Narrative</i>.
2nd ed. Toronto: University of Toronto Press, 1997. </p>
<p> Barthes, Roland.&nbsp; "Introduction to the Structural Analysis of
Narratives" in <i>Image-Music-Text</i>, reprinted in <i>A Barthes
Reader</i> ed. Susan Sontag. Hill &amp; Wang, 1982. 251-295. </p>
<p> Chatman, Seymour.&nbsp; <i>Coming to Terms: The Rhetoric of
Narrative in Fiction and Film</i>. Ithaca, NY: Cornell, 1990. </p>
<p> Chatman, Seymour.&nbsp; <i>Story and Discourse: Narrative Structure
in Fiction and Film</i>.<i> </i>Ithaca, NY: Cornell, 1981. </p>
<p> Cohn, Dorrit. <i>The Distinction of Fiction</i>. Baltimore, MD:
Johns Hopkins University Press, 1999. </p>
<p>Cohn, Dorrit. <i>Transparent Minds: Narrative Modes for Presenting
Consciousness in Fiction</i>. Princeton, NJ: Princeton University
Press, 1978. </p>
<p> Duchan, Judith F., Gail A. Bruder, and Lynne E. Hewitt (1995). <i>Deixis
in Narrative: A Cognitive Science Perspective</i>. <a href="../../Abstracts/Deixis_95.html">Contents and abstracts</a>. </p>
<p> Fludernick, Monika (ed.). Special Issue: Second Person Narrative. <i>Style</i>
28. 3 (Fall 1994). </p>
<p> Fludernick, Monika (ed.). Bibliographical Issue: Second Person
Narrative. <i>Style</i> 28. 4 (Winter 1994). See Schofield below. </p>
<p> Genette, Gerard.&nbsp; <i>Narrative Discourse: An Essay in Method</i>
trans. J.E. Lewin (Cornell, 1980). </p>
<p> Herman, David. Textual 'You' and double deixis in Edna O'Brien's <i>A
Pagan Place</i>. <i>Style</i> 28 .3 (Fall, 1994): 378 (33 pages). <a href="../../Abstracts/Herman_94.html">Full text</a>. </p>
<p> Kermode, Frank.&nbsp; <i>The Genesis of Secrecy: On the
Interpretation of   Narrative</i>. Boston, MA: Harvard, 1979). </p>
<p>Lule, Jack. <i>Daily News, Eternal Stories: The Mythological Role
of Journalism</i>.   New York: Guilford Press, 2001. The Guilford
communication series. <a href="http://www.cjr.org/year/01/2/hanson.asp">Reviewed
by Christopher Hanson</a> in <i>Columbia Journalism Review</i>
(external). </p>
<p> Martin, Wallace.&nbsp; <i>Recent Theories of Narrative</i>. Ithaca,
NY: Cornell,   1986. </p>
<p>Niles, John D. <i>Homo Narrans: The Poetics and Anthropology of
Oral Literature</i>.   Philadelphia, PA: University of Pennsylvania
Press, 1999. <a href="http://www.upenn.edu/pennpress/book/13339.html">Publisher's
presentation</a>. <a href="http://ist-socrates.berkeley.edu/%7Eniles/nilesimages3.html">Author's
site</a>. </p>
<p>Pavel, Thomas G. Narrative Tectonics. <i>Poetics Today</i> 11. 2
(Summer 1990):   349-64. </p>
<p> Pavel, Thomas G. Some Remarks on Narrative Grammars. <i>Linguistic
Perspectives on Literature</i>. London, 1980. 187-212. </p>
<p>Pavel, Thomas G. Formalism in Narrative Semiotics. <i>Poetics Today</i>
9, 3 (1988): 593-606. </p>
<p> Prince, Gerald.&nbsp; <i>A Dictionary of Narratology</i>. Nebraska,
1987. </p>
<p> Rimon-Kenan, Shlomith.&nbsp; <i>Narrative Fiction: Contemporary
Poetics</i>. London: Methuen, 1983. </p>
<p> Ryan, Marie-Laure. <i>Possible worlds, artificial intelligence, and
narrative theory</i>. Bloomington: Indiana University Press, 1991. </p>
<p> Shank, Robert G.&nbsp; <i>Tell Me a Story: Narrative and
Intelligence</i>. Northwestern, 1995. </p>
<p> Schofield, Dennis. A Bibliography of Second-Person Fiction and
Related Critical Theory. <a href="http://www.westnet.com.au/emmas/2p/thesis/bib_1.htm">Full text</a>
(external). </p>
<p>White, Hayden.&nbsp; <i>The Content of the Form: Narrative
Discourse and Historical Representation</i> (Johns Hopkins, 1987). <br>
&nbsp; </p>
<p><b>Folklore</b> </p>
<p>Brunvand, Jan Harold&nbsp; (1999). <i>Too Good To Be True: The
Colossal Book of Urban Legends</i>. <a href="http://deseretnews.com/dn/view/1,1249,115009718,00.html?">Review</a>
(external). <br>
&nbsp; </p>
<p><a name="Cognitive"></a><b><font color="#009900"><font size="+1">Cognitive
Approaches to Narrative</font></font></b> </p>
<p>Banfield, Ann (1982), <i>Unspeakable Sentences: Narration and
Representation in the Language of Fiction</i>. Boston: Routledge &amp;
Kegan Paul. </p>
<p>Bruner, Jerome S. (1986), <i>Actual Minds, Possible Worlds</i>,
Cambridge, MA: Harvard University Press. </p>
<p><a name="Duchan, Bruder &amp; Hewitt (1995)"></a>Duchan, Judith F., Gail
A. Bruder, and Lynne E. Hewitt (1995). <i>Deixis in Narrative: A
Cognitive Science Perspective</i>. Hillsdale, NJ: Lawrence Erlbaum. 522
pp. <a href="../../Abstracts/Deixis_95.html">Contents and abstracts</a>.<a href="http://www.cs.buffalo.edu/pub/WWW/faculty/rapaport/graesser.rev.forhtml/">Reviewed
by Arthur Graesser and Cheryl Bowers in <i>Minds and Machines</i> (1996)</a>
(external). </p>
<p>Graesser, Arthur C., Murray Singer, and Tom Trabasso (1994).
Constructing Inferences During Narrative Text Comprehension. <i>Psychological
Review</i> 101, pp. 371-395. </p>
<p>Kreuz, Roger J., &amp; MacNealy, Mary Sue (eds.) (1996), <i>Three
Obstacles in Empirical Research on Aesthetic and Literary Comprehension</i>,
Norwood, NJ: Ablex. </p>
<p>Schank, Roger C. (1990), <i>Tell Me a Story: A New Look at Real and
Artificial Memory</i>, New York: Praeger. </p>
<p>Schank, Roger C., &amp; Riesbeck, Christopher K. (1981), <i>Inside
Computer Understanding: Five Programs Plus Miniatures</i>, Hillsdale,
NJ: Lawrence Erlbaum. </p>
<p>Winner, Ellen (1982). <i>Invented Worlds: The Psychology of the Arts</i>.
Cambridge, MA: Harvard University Press. <br>
&nbsp; </p>
<p><a name="Neuroscience"></a><font color="#009900"><font size="+1">Neuroscience
Approaches to Narrative</font></font> </p>
<p> Denes, Gianfranco, Shirin Sarkari, Arlene A. Tan, Dennis L. Molfese,
and Francesca Happe. <br>
Language and communication in developmental disorders. <i>Handbook of
Neurolinguistics</i>. Ed. Brigitte Stemmer, Harry A. Whitaker, et al.
San Diego, CA: Academic Press, 1998 (pp. 507-534). </p>
<p> <a href="../../CogSci/Autism.html#DSM">DSM-IV's definition of autism</a> </p>
<p> Fletcher, P. C., F. Happe, F. Frith, U. Baker, S. C. et al. Other
minds in the brain: A functional imaging study of "theory of mind" in
story comprehension. <i>Cognition</i> 57. 2 (Nov 1995), 109-128. <a href="../../CogSci/Autism.html#Fletcheretal1995">Abstract</a>. </p>
<p>Goel, Vinod, Jordan Grafman, Norihiro Sadato, and Mark Hallett.
Modeling   other minds. <i>Neuroreport</i> 1995 (5 pages). <a href="../../Abstracts/Goel_Grafman_95.html">Abstract</a>. </p>
<p>Grafman, Jordan. Similarities and distinctions among current models
of prefrontal cortical functions. <i>ANYAS</i> 1995 (31 pages).&nbsp; <a href="../../Abstracts/Grafman_95.html">Abstract</a>. </p>
<p>Grafman, Jordan et al. Script generation as an indicator of
knowledge representation in patients with Alzheimer's disease. <i>Brain
&amp; Language</i>, 1991 (15 pages). <a href="../../Abstracts/Grafman_91.html">Abstract</a>. </p>
<p> Happe, Francesca G. E. The autobiographical writings of three
Asperger syndrome adults: Problems of interpretation and implications
for theory. <i>Autism and Asperger Syndrome</i>. Ed. Uta Frith et al.
Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1991 (pp. 207-242). <a href="../../CogSci/Autism.html#Happe1991">Abstract</a>. </p>
<p> Happe, Francesca G. Understanding minds and metaphors: Insights from
the study of figurative language in autism. <i>Metaphor &amp; Symbol</i>
10. 4 (1995): 275-295. <a href="../../CogSci/Autism.html#Happe1995">Abstract</a>.</p>
<p> Happe, Francesca G. E. Communicative competence and theory of mind
in autism: A test of relevance theory. <i>Cognition</i> 48.2 (Aug
1993): 101-119. <a href="../../CogSci/Autism.html#Happe1993">Abstract</a>.</p>
<p>Nichelli, Paolo et al. Where the brain appreciates the moral of a
story. <i>Neuroreport</i>. 1995 (4 pages).&nbsp; <a href="../../Abstracts/Nichelli_95.html">Abstract</a>. </p>
<p>Partiot, Arnaud et al. Brain activation during the generation of
non-emotional and emotional plans. <i>Neuroreport</i>, 1995 (4
pages).&nbsp;&nbsp; <a href="../../Abstracts/Partiot_95.html">Abstract</a>.</p>
<p>Sirigu, Angela et al. Encoding of sequence and boundaries of scripts
following prefrontal lesions. <i>Cortex</i>, 1996 (13 pages). <a href="../../Abstracts/Sirigu_96.html">Abstract</a>.<br>
</p>
<p>Wheeler, Mark A., Donald T. Stuss, and Endel Tulving (1997). Toward
a theory of episodic memory: the frontal lobes and autonoetic
consciousness. Psychological Bulletin 121. 3: 331-354.&nbsp; <a href="../../Abstracts/Wheeler_97.html">Abstract</a>.<br>
 </p>

